You need to create a `JmsMessageContainerFactory` and configure it accordingly. Spring Boot creates one for you but you can create as much instances as you want with your own customizations and refer them using the `containerFactory` of the `@JmsListener` annotation.

    @Bean
    public DefaultJmsListenerContainerFactory jmsListenerContainerFactory(
			ConnectionFactory connectionFactory) {
      DefaultJmsListenerContainerFactory factory = new DefaultJmsListenerContainerFactory();
      factory.setConnectionFactory(connectionFactory);
      factory.setMessageConverter(yourMessageConverter());
      // .. other settings
      return factory;
    }

Note that the bean name here is the default name so you don&#39;t need to specify a `connectionFactory` attribute.

Spring Boot 1.4 will [auto-detect your `MessageConverter`](https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-boot/pull/4284) and assign it to the default factory it auto-creates for you.

You could just define a converter like this
```
@Component
public MyConverter implements MessageConverter {
    @Override
    ...toMessage(...)

    @Override
    ...fromMessage(...)
```
Because you have it annotated with @Component you don&#39;t need to define either JmsTemplate (to set the converter on it for sending) or define DefaultJmsListenerContainerFactory.

Realise though, that if you do define those two classes, you have to set the converter onto both as suggested by Stephane

